  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Requesting a Change of Name
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To name things by their kind is the way of order,
    yet none surpasses the virtue of humility.
    Though my name has been inscribed in the royal court,
    I dare not presume to alter it without reason.
    Thus I submit this memorial with utmost reverence and trembling.

    Consider how the customs of our small realm
    have always honored continuity with the past—
    a practice rooted in the Imperial decree:
    "Let not the beginning be changed."
    Yet since I was named Qi, bearing the seal of our ancestral domain,
    from the grand halls of government to the humble streets of villages,
    wherever characters are written with the radical of spirit,
    when the character Qi appears alongside it,
    its sound so mirrors, its form so resembles,
    that all must avoid it—
    this is deemed the proper custom.

    Only after long years did I perceive
    how much this brings impediment to affairs.
    Yet I cannot override the will of the people;
    I see now that changing it myself brings the greatest ease.

    My great-grandfather, King Chungnyeol, bore the taboo name Shim,
    which he changed to Geol.
    My grandfather, King Chungseon, bore the taboo name Won,
    which he changed to Zhang.
    Looking to the origins of these precedents,
    all followed this very path.

    Now I humbly seek to take Chuan as my name.
    If Your Majesty would graciously extend an ear to my plea,
    and permit me this modest alteration,
    I swear by unchanging integrity to govern the eastern realm,
    to bring honor to my ancestors,
    and to devote my whole heart to your northern throne,
    that I may repay the boundless grace of your nurture.
  footnotes:
    - The taboo names (諱) referenced belonged to Suk's royal ancestors; changing one's own name to avoid homophonic conflict with such taboos was a common practice in East Asian courts.
    - The 'northern throne' (北闕) is a respectful reference to the royal palace and its authority.
